      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "OpenMS is not mentioned in any of the provided passages. The paper mentions other simulators (Mspire-Simulator, JAMSS, OpenMS-Simulator, MSAcquisition Simulator, SMITER) in a related-works section but does not describe OpenMS as a post-simulation tool used with ViMMS output.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "OpenMS \u2014 Optional post-simulation tool for peak picking and fragmentation coverage analysis on mzML output",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:05.390197+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Once chemical objects have been prepared (whether for single- or multi-sample settings), different fragmentation strategies can be run. Fragmentation strategies are implemented as controllers that extend from the base Controller class. Controllers are executed in the context of an environment bringing together input chemicals, mass spectrometer and controllers as a single context (Figure 1D).",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed: the workflow is chemicals \u2192 mass spectrometer simulation \u2192 controllers (fragmentation strategies).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this skill as the second step after generating or extracting chemicals, immediately before attaching a controller to orchestrate the fragmentation strategy.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:05.390197+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Chemicals are input objects to the simulation process in ViMMS 2.0, and can be generated in different ways: either in a purely synthetic manner (e.g. sampling their properties from databases or fixed statistical distributions) or by construction from existing data (mzML files) via the extraction of RoI traces.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms mzML extraction capability, but the specific class name 'ChemicalMixtureFromMZML' is not mentioned. The paper describes the functionality (extraction from mzML files) but not the exact class name.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Your chemicals are already represented as raw spectrum objects or mzML files without extracted m/z/RT/intensity metadata; use ChemicalMixtureFromMZML first.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:05.390197+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Note that the modularity of the mass spectrometry and environment classes means it is possible to swap purely simulated MS and environment implementation with alternatives that control an actual MS instrument while other aspects remain unchanged. In other work, we demonstrated the practicality of this idea by building alternative implementations of these classes that use the Thermo Fisher IAPI (Thermo Fisher Scientific, n.d.) for bridging, making it possible for fragmentation strategies to be executed in simulation as well as unchanged on Thermo Tribrid Fusion instruments (Davies et al., 2021).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms ViMMS can use idealized simulation or swap to real instrument control (Thermo Tribrid Fusion via IAPI), but does not explicitly state that ViMMS provides 'idealized independent mass detection' or discuss limitations regarding instrument-specific hardware behavior like Orbitrap resolution or Q-TOF drift.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectrometer-simulator-configuration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You need to simulate instrument-specific hardware behavior (e.g., Thermo Orbitrap resolution curves, Agilent Q-TOF drift); ViMMS provides idealized independent mass detection.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:05.390197+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-detection-and-acquisition-performance-benchmarking/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Code is provided to compute various evaluation metrics, such as coverage and intensities of fragmented precursors. This allows users to benchmark different controller implementations comparatively. Two enhanced DDA controllers (named SmartROI and WeightedDEW, outlined by Davies et al. (2021)) are also provided that demonstrate how novel fragmentation strategies could be rapidly implemented and validated in ViMMS 2.0.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly supports comparative benchmarking of fragmentation strategies (WeightedDEW and TopN mentioned), coverage metrics, and intensity evaluation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-detection-and-acquisition-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "A comparative evaluation skill for quantifying how well different tandem MS fragmentation strategies (e.g., WeightedDEW with exclusion vs. TopN) detect and acquire metabolite spectra in virtual LC-MS/MS experiments. This skill measures coverage metrics, intensity profiles, and MS",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:24.289143+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-detection-and-acquisition-performance-benchmarking/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "ViMMS 2.0 is a software framework that can be used to develop new fragmentation strategies in metabolomics completely in-silico as well as on mass spectrometry instruments. The framework allows users to generate chemical objects (produced synthetically or extracted from existing mzML files) and simulate a tandem mass spectrometry process, where different fragmentation strategies can be rapidly implemented, tested and evaluated.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms ViMMS 2.0 (case-insensitive match to VIMMS) as the core framework for simulating fragmentation strategies with chemical objects and mzML input/output.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-detection-and-acquisition-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "VIMMS as core simulation framework for running fragmentation controllers (TopNController, WeightedDEWController) against virtual chemical mixtures and capturing EvaluationData and mzML output",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:24.289143+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-detection-and-acquisition-performance-benchmarking/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "OpenMS is not mentioned in any passage. The paper does not describe post-processing of mzML output with OpenMS or MZMine. Paper mentions evaluation metrics are computed internally within ViMMS 2.0 framework itself.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-03990",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-detection-and-acquisition-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
